OAB - Data on the menstrual history, family history, and degree of obesity of 1374 
      Vancouver nursing students were collected in 1945 and from 1947-56. In 1979, 768 
      of these women were located; 726 responded (94%) and participated in a follow-up 
      study, providing information on their subsequent medical history and on 
      breast-related problems. No major differences were found between the early 
      histories of these participants and those who were not located or did not 
      respond. Among the respondents, 215 gave a history of symptoms compatible with 
      benign breast disease (BBD); in 107 cases, this diagnosis was confirmed by 
      biopsy. By age 50, the cumulative risk for BBD was 17% for biopsied and 31% for 
      symptomatic disease. Biopsied BBD was associated with premenstrual breast 
      discomfort, irregular menses, a history of abortions, a family history of both 
      benign and malignant breast disease, lack of use of oral contraceptives, a low 
      index of obesity and small breasts, obesity and breast size being independent. 
      Factors associated with symptomatic BBD were usually associated with a greater 
      likelihood of biopsy for symptomatic disease; hence, the relative risks for 
      biopsied disease were generally greater than those for symptomatic disease. 
      Although the risk factors for BBD differ from those for breast cancer, the 
      findings are consistent with the hypothesis of excessive circulating estrogen. 
      (author's)
