DP  - 1981 Aug 15
TI  - Flow cytometry of breast carcinoma: II. Relation of tumor cell cycle distribution 
      to histology and estrogen receptor.
PG  - 985-8
AB  - Flow cytometry analysis of cell cycle distribution was carried out on 
      acridine-orange-stained cell suspensions freshly prepared from carcinoma of the 
      breast of 90 women, and compared with control, benign breast specimens from 10 
      women. There was a significantly greater proportion of cells in S (9.1% +/- 5.8) 
      and G2 + M (8.0 +/- 6.0) phases of the cycle in breast cancer specimens than in 
      the S (1.5% +/- 0.6) and G2 + M (2.5 +/- 0.9) phases of the cycle in benign, 
      control specimens of breast tissue. Great variation was noted among the breast 
      cancers, with medullary carcinomas having the highest percentage of cells in S + 
      G2 + M, and papillary, tubular, colloid and well-differentiated duct carcinomas 
      having the lowest. Tumors from premenopausal women classified as estrogen 
      receptor negative had significantly more cells in S + G2 + M than did tumors from 
      postmenopausal women that were estrogen-receptor positive.
